Here are the fixes for each issue when moving to .NET 10:

### 1. `[InlineArray]` with explicit `StructLayout`
.NET 10 now **ignores** the explicit `Size` in `StructLayout` on inline array types — the runtime computes size as `element size × length`. Remove the explicit layout:

```csharp
// Before
[InlineArray(16)]
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit, Size = 64)]
struct MyBuffer { private byte _element; }

// After — drop the StructLayout entirely
[InlineArray(16)]
struct MyBuffer { private byte _element; }
```

If you relied on padding/trailing bytes from `Size = 64`, you'll need to adjust.

### 2. `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux
.NET 10 returns the **actual kernel filesystem name** (e.g., `ext4`, `tmpfs`) instead of the generic mount type. Update string comparisons:

```csharp
// Before (returned generic types)
if (drive.DriveFormat == "ext2")

// After (returns real fs name)
if (drive.DriveFormat == "ext4")
```

Review all `DriveFormat` comparisons for correct kernel-level names.

### 3. NU1510 warnings (pruned package references)
.NET 10 SDK enables **NuGet package reference pruning** by default. Transitive packages that are unnecessary are pruned, producing NU1510. Options:

- **Preferred:** Remove the unnecessary `<PackageReference>` entries flagged by the warning.
- **Suppress temporarily:** Add `<SuppressTfmSupportBuildWarnings>true</SuppressTfmSupportBuildWarnings>` or set the warning to `NoWarn`.

### 4. Transitive NuGet vulnerability auditing
.NET 10 changes `NuGetAuditMode` default from `direct` to **`all`**, so transitive dependencies are now audited. You'll see new warnings. Options:

- **Preferred:** Update vulnerable transitive packages or pin safe versions with `<PackageReference Include="..." VersionOverride="..." />`.
- **Revert behavior:** Set `<NuGetAuditMode>direct</NuGetAuditMode>` in your project (not recommended long-term).

### 5. `FilePatternMatch.Stem` nullability
In .NET 10, `Stem` changed from `string?` to **`string`** (non-nullable). It now returns `string.Empty` instead of `null`. Update checks:

```csharp
// Before
if (match.Stem is null) { ... }

// After
if (match.Stem.Length == 0) { ... }
// or
if (match.Stem == string.Empty) { ... }
```

The `null` check will never be true in .NET 10, so existing logic would silently break.
